The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Nation | Nation Briefs
                                                                                                                 NATION BRIEFS
                                      
	 Mumbai, July 26 (PTI): A film producer-director was arrested today after a girl alleged that he had raped her on the pretext of giving a role in his films.           
	The 24-year-old girl had gone to an audition held by Ramkumar Kumawat, who has directed some small budget films, police said. She was asked to come to his office where she was allegedly raped.                   
	 Mumbai (PTI): Eleven persons, including four women, were arrested and a small quantity of cocaine was seized from them during a raid at an apartment in south Mumbai on Sunday. A raid was conducted after a tip-off that the drug was being taken during a party at the apartment, an official said.                  
	 Colombo (PTI): India and Sri Lanka will resume ferry services between the countries, starting with one connecting Kochi and Colombo. The infrastructure has been put in place, Sri Lanka transport minister Dullas Alahapperuma told a meeting of Saarc transport ministers in Colombo.                   
	 Mumbai (PTI): A special anti-terror court will give its verdict on the August 2003 Mumbai twin blasts case on Monday. The blasts at the India Gate and Zhaveri Bazar had killed 52 people and injured 100. The judgment will be the biggest in the country the conviction of 100 accused in the 1993 serial blasts case.                  
	 New Delhi (PTI): Delhi Metro has decided to introduce air-conditioned CNG feeder buses and has placed an order for 300 vehicles. The first lot of 75 buses will be delivered within six months. Each bus will cost Rs 19.8 lakh, an official said.                  
	 Bhubaneswar: A 23-year-old woman lodged a police complaint on Sunday claiming to be the daughter of Orissa MLA Arabinda Dhali, reports our correspondent. Sanjita Dhali said she was the daughter of Dhalis first wife and demanded a DNA test. The BJD MLA said the allegation was a conspiracy.                                                                                                                           
